		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />*hey mods, split the Linux discussion to another topic*
<br />
<br />I've tried out AndLinux, basically "Linux For Windows".  It's a distribution of CoLinux that somewhat works out of the box.  (Only thing really broken out of the box is Unicode support for accessing the C drive).
<br />You get a GUI, and can run some KDE applications, like Konqueror, and also can run the Synaptic package manager to get packages from Ubuntu.
<br />You can even run Wine.
<br />Only problem is that the Windows side and Linux side don't like talking to each other, and can only communicate through a virtual network card.  X is super-super slow.  Also, installed applications aren't added to any menus anywhere, so you need to run them from a terminal.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


